8 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
9
10 PART I. NC UNIFORM ELECTRONIC WILLS ACT
11 SECTION 1.1. Chapter 31 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
12 Article to read:
13 "Article 11.
14 "North Carolina Uniform Electronic Wills Act.
15 "§ 31-71. Short title.
16 This Article may be cited as the "North Carolina Uniform Electronic Wills Act."
17 "§ 31-72. Definitions.
18 In this Article, the following definitions apply:
19 (1) Electronic. – Relating to technology having electrical, digital, magnetic,
20 wireless, optical, electromagnetic, or similar capabilities.
21 (2) Reserved for future codification purposes.
22 (3) Electronic will. – A will executed electronically in compliance with
23 G.S. 31-74(a) or an attested written will that has been stored in electronic form
24 in compliance with G.S. 31-79.
25 (4) Record. – Information that is inscribed on a tangible medium or that is stored
26 in an electronic or other medium and is retrievable in perceivable form.
27 (5) Sign. – With present intent to authenticate or adopt a record, to do either of
28 the following:
29 a. To execute or adopt a tangible symbol.
30 b. To affix to or logically associate with the record an electronic symbol
31 or process.
32 (6) State. – Consists of the following:
33 a. A state of the United States, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, the
34 United States Virgin Islands, or any territory or insular possession
35 subject to the jurisdiction of the United States.
*H377-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 b. An Indian tribe or band or Alaskan native village that is recognized by
2 federal law or formally acknowledged by an entity listed in
3 sub-subdivision a. of this subdivision.
4 "§ 31-73. Law applicable to electronic will; principles of equity.
5 An electronic will is a will for all purposes of the law of this State. The law of this State
6 applicable to wills and principles of equity applies to an electronic will, except as modified by
7 this Article.
8 "§ 31-74. Execution of electronic will.
9 (a) An electronic will shall be executed in accordance with all of the following:
10 (1) Recorded in electronic form and readable as text at the time of signing.
11 (2) Signed by the testator.
12 (3) Attested by at least two competent witnesses as provided by G.S. 31-3.3.
13 (b) The validity of a will executed electronically but not in compliance with subsection
14 (a) of this section is governed by G.S. 31-46.
15 "§ 31-75. Revocation.
16 (a) An electronic will may revoke all or part of a previous will.
17 (b) All or part of an electronic will may be revoked in either of the following ways:
18 (1) In the manner provided by G.S. 31-5.1(1).
19 (2) By a physical act, if it is established by a preponderance of the evidence that
20 the testator, with the intent of revoking all or part of the electronic will,
21 performed the act or directed another individual who performed the act in the
22 testator's physical presence.
23 "§ 31-76. Electronic will attested and made self-proved at time of execution.
24 (a) An electronic will may be self-proved by acknowledgment of the testator and
25 affidavits of the witnesses as provided by G.S. 31-11.6, so long as the acknowledgment of the
26 testator and the affidavits of the witnesses are made simultaneously with the execution of the
27 electronic will.
28 (b) A signature physically or electronically affixed to an acknowledgment or affidavit
29 that is affixed to or logically associated with an electronic will is deemed a signature of the
30 electronic will.
31 "§ 31-77. Certification of paper copy.
32 (a) An individual may create a certified paper copy of an electronic will by certifying that
33 a paper copy of the electronic will is a complete, true, and accurate copy of the electronic will.
34 The certification shall be in the form of an affidavit sworn to or affirmed before an officer
35 authorized to administer oaths. If the electronic will is made self-proved, the certified paper copy
36 of the will shall include the affidavits. The certified paper copy of the electronic will may be
37 created at any time after the electronic will is executed.
38 (b) A certified paper copy of an electronic will, but not the electronic will itself, may be
39 probated under G.S. 28A-2A-8(a1).
40 "§ 31-78. Uniformity of application and construction.
41 In applying and construing this Article, consideration must be given to the need to promote
42 uniformity of the law with respect to its subject matter among states that enact the Uniform
43 Electronic Wills Act.
44 "§ 31-79. Conversion of attested written will to electronic will.
45 (a) At any time during the life of the testator, the testator, or another person at the
46 testator's direction, may convert an attested written will to an electronic will by storing the
47 attested written will as an electronic record. The electronic record shall include a certification,
48 signed by the person who has converted the attested written will to an electronic will, in the form
49 of an affidavit sworn to or affirmed before an officer authorized to administer oaths, that the
50 electronic form of the attested written will is a complete, true, and accurate copy of the attested
51 written will. If the person converting the attested written will to an electronic will is not the
Page 2 House Bill 377-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 testator, the certification shall also contain a statement that the testator expressly authorized the
2 conversion of the attested written will to an electronic will.
3 (b) If the attested written will is lost or destroyed after being converted to an electronic
4 will, the loss or destruction shall not be deemed a revocation of the attested written will, nor shall
5 it be deemed a presumption of revocation of the attested written will."
