16 PART IV. REVISIONS TO YEAR'S ALLOWANCE STATUTES
17 SECTION 4.1. G.S. 30-15 reads as rewritten:
18 "§ 30-15. When spouse entitled to allowance.
19 (a) Every surviving spouse of a decedent, whether or not the surviving spouse has
20 petitioned for an elective share, shall be entitled to receive an allowance having the value of sixty
21 thousand dollars ($60,000) for the surviving spouse's support for one year after the death of the
22 deceased spouse unless the spouse is barred from seeking an allowance under G.S. 31A-1 or
23 another applicable law. The spouse's allowance shall be in addition to the spouse's share of the
24 decedent's estate if the decedent died intestate but shall be charged against the spouse's share of
25 the decedent's estate if the decedent died testate.
26 (b) The right of a surviving spouse to file a claim for an allowance must be exercised
27 during the lifetime of the surviving spouse by (i) the surviving spouse, (ii) the surviving spouse's
28 agent under a durable power of attorney, or (iii), with approval of the court, by the guardian of
29 the surviving spouse's estate or general guardian. A claim for an allowance must be made by
30 filing a verified petition with the clerk of court of the county in which venue would be proper
31 under G.S. 28A-3-1. There is no time limitation on bringing a claim for an allowance except that,
32 if a personal representative has been appointed for the decedent's estate, the claim must be made
33 within six months after the issuance of letters testamentary or letters of administration. In
34 addition, if a personal representative has been appointed for the decedent's estate, a copy of the
35 verified petition must be personally delivered or sent by first-class mail by the petitioner to the
36 personal representative.
37 (c) If the surviving spouse dies after the petition is filed but before the claim for an
38 allowance has been fully satisfied, any deficiency judgment existing at the time of the surviving
39 spouse's death shall not expire.
40 (d) The spouse's allowance shall be exempt from any lien by judgment or execution
41 against the property of the decedent or any other claim made against or owed by the decedent's
42 estate. The spouse's allowance takes priority over any child's allowance under
43 G.S. 30-17.G.S. 30-17, except as set forth in subsection (e) of this section.
44 (e) If a surviving spouse entitled to an allowance fails to file a petition for an allowance
45 within six months after the date of death of the decedent and an eligible person files a petition
46 for a child's allowance in accordance with G.S. 30-17 before the spouse files a petition for an
47 allowance, then the spouse's priority to receive the allowance prior to the child named in the
48 petition is waived and the clerk may proceed to assign the full child's allowance to the eligible
49 child named in the petition. If a petition for the spousal allowance is filed jointly with a petition
50 for a child's allowance, then the spouse retains the right to receive the allowance prior to the child
51 named in the petition. The waiver described in this subsection shall not affect the spouse's right
Page 8 House Bill 377-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 to an allowance, only the spouse's priority to receive an allowance over any child's allowance
2 under G.S. 30-17.
3 (f) A proceeding for a spouse's allowance shall be an estate proceeding governed by the
4 provisions of Article 2 of Chapter 28 of the General Statutes."
5 SECTION 4.2. G.S. 30-17 reads as rewritten:
6 "§ 30-17. When children entitled to an allowance.
7 (a) Every child of a decedent who is under the age of 21 years at the time of the decedent's
8 death, including an adopted child or a child in utero, and every child who is under the age of 21
9 years at the time of the decedent's death with whom the decedent stood in loco parentis at the
10 time of death, shall be entitled to receive an allowance having a value of ten thousand dollars
11 ($10,000) for the child's support for one year after the death of the decedent. The allowance shall
12 be in addition to the child's share of the decedent's estate regardless of whether the decedent died
13 testate or intestate.
14 (b) The right of a child to file a claim for an allowance must be exercised during the
15 lifetime of the child by the person with priority to file on behalf of the child as provided in
16 subsection (c) of this section. A claim for an allowance must be made by filing a verified petition
17 with the clerk of court of the county in which venue would be proper under G.S. 28A-3-1. There
18 is no time limitation on bringing a claim for an allowance except that, if a personal representative
19 has been appointed for the decedent's estate, the claim must be made within six months after the
20 issuance of letters testamentary or letters of administration. In addition, if a personal
21 representative has been appointed for the decedent's estate, a copy of the verified petition must
22 be personally delivered or sent by first-class mail by the petitioner to the personal representative.
23 (c) The person entitled to file a petition on behalf of the child for a child's allowance shall
24 be in the following order of priority:
25 (1) The child, if the child is at least 18 years old or an emancipated minor at the
26 time of the filing of the petition.
27 (1)(2) The general guardian or guardian of the estate of the child, if any.
28 (2)(3) The surviving parent of the child if the child resides with the surviving parent.
29 (3)(4) The person with whom the child resides.
30 If the clerk of court determines that no person entitled to file a petition pursuant to this
31 subsection is a fit or suitable individual, the clerk, upon the clerk's own motion, may appoint
32 another individual if the clerk determines that individual better represents the best interests of the
33 child as the representative.
34 (d) The child's allowance shall be exempt from any lien by judgment or execution against
35 the property of the decedent or any other claim made against or owed by the decedent's estate
36 except that the spouse's allowance under G.S. 30-15 shall take priority over any child's allowance.
37 A child's allowance shall only be awarded after the full spouse's allowance under G.S. 30-15 has
38 been awarded.
39 (e) A proceeding for a child's allowance shall be an estate proceeding governed by the
40 provisions of Article 2 of Chapter 28 of the General Statutes."
41 SECTION 4.3. G.S. 30-20 reads as rewritten:
42 "§ 30-20. Procedure for assignment; order of clerk.
43 (a) The clerk of court shall first ascertain if the surviving spouse is entitled to an
44 allowance according to the provisions of this Article, and, if so, enter an order setting forth the
45 personal property of the estate to be awarded to the surviving spouse. Once the spouse's
46 allowance has been awarded, the clerk of court shall next ascertain if any children of the decedent
47 are entitled to an allowance according to the provisions of this Article, and, if so, enter an order
48 setting forth the personal property of the estate to be awarded for the child's allowance. If a
49 personal representative has been appointed for the decedent's estate, the clerk of court shall
50 provide a copy of any order awarding an allowance to the personal representative of the
51 decedent's estate.
House Bill 377-Second Edition Page 9

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) If the personal property of the estate is insufficient to satisfy the allowances awarded,
2 the clerk of the superior court shall enter judgment against the decedent's estate for the amount
3 of the deficiency. If a personal representative has been appointed for the decedent's estate, the
4 deficiency shall be satisfied by the personal representative when a sufficiency of such assets shall
5 come into the possession of the personal representative.
6 (c) The clerk of court may, on the clerk's own motion, determine that a hearing is
7 necessary to determine whether a year's allowance should be awarded pursuant to the provisions
8 of this Article and, if so, what personal property should be awarded. If the clerk of court makes
9 such a determination, the clerk shall direct the petitioner to commence a contested estate
10 proceeding pursuant to G.S. 30-23 in order to determine the year's allowance."
11 SECTION 4.4. G.S. 30-23.1 reads as rewritten:
12 "§ 30-23.1. Contested proceeding regarding allowance.
13 (a) If no contested estate proceeding under G.S. 30-20(c) was commenced by the
14 petitioner or by order of the clerk joining respondents to the proceeding to determine an award
15 of an allowance under this Article, any person with standing, including the personal
16 representative of the decedent's estate, may bring a proceeding to challenge the award of a spousal
17 allowance or a child's allowance, including, but not limited to, a proceeding to challenge the
18 validity of an award of a year's allowance, a proceeding to challenge the amount of a year's
19 allowance awarded, and a proceeding to challenge the assets awarded as part of a year's
20 allowance. If a contested estate proceeding was commenced under G.S. 30-20(c), by the
21 petitioner or by order of the clerk joining the respondents to the proceeding to determine an award
22 of an allowance under this Article, then any person with standing, including the personal
23 representative of the decedent's estate, who was not a party to the contested estate proceeding
24 may bring a proceeding in accordance with this section.
25 (b) Any proceeding to challenge the award of the allowance brought pursuant to this
26 section shall be conducted as an estate proceeding in accordance with the provisions of Article 2
27 of Chapter 28A of the General Statutes and must be brought within one year of the date the order
28 awarding the year's allowance was entered."
29 SECTION 4.5. G.S. 28A-25-6 reads as rewritten:
30 "§ 28A-25-6. Payment to clerk of money owed decedent.
31 (a) As an alternative to the small estate settlement procedures of this Article, any person
32 indebted to a decedent may satisfy such indebtedness by paying the amount of the debt to the
33 clerk of the superior court of the county of the domicile of the decedent if all of the following
34 conditions are met:
35 (1) No administrator has been appointed.
36 (2) Except as otherwise provided in G.S. 90-210.64(d), the amount owed by such
37 person does not exceed five thousand dollars ($5,000).
38 (3) Except as otherwise provided in G.S. 90-210.64(d), the sum tendered to the
39 clerk would not make the aggregate sum which has come into the clerk's hands
40 belonging to the decedent exceed five thousand dollars ($5,000).
41 (b) Such payments may not be made to the clerk if the total amount paid or tendered with
42 respect to any one decedent would exceed five thousand dollars ($5,000), even though
43 disbursements have been made so that the aggregate amount in the clerk's hands at any one time
44 would not exceed five thousand dollars ($5,000).
45 (c) If the sum tendered pursuant to this section would make the aggregate sum coming
46 into the clerk's hands with respect to any one decedent exceed five thousand dollars ($5,000) the
47 clerk shall appoint an administrator, or the sum may be administered under the preceding sections
48 of this Article.
49 (d) If it appears to the clerk after making a preliminary survey that disbursements
50 pursuant to this section would not exhaust funds received pursuant to this section, the clerk may,
Page 10 House Bill 377-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 in the clerk's discretion, appoint an administrator, or the funds may be administered under the
2 preceding sections of this Article.
3 (e) The receipt from the clerk of the superior court of a payment purporting to be made
4 pursuant to this section is a full release to the debtor for the payment so made.
5 (f) If no administrator has been appointed, the clerk of superior court shall, upon motion
6 of the clerk or upon the application of an interested party, disburse the money received under this
7 section for the following purposes and in the following order:
8 (1) To pay the surviving spouse's year's allowance and children's year's allowance
9 assigned in accordance with law.law, except that if (i) it has been greater than
10 six months since the date of death of the decedent and (ii) there has been no
11 petition filed and assignment of a spouse's or child's year's allowance, the clerk
12 may disburse the money received under this section in accordance with the
13 other provisions of this subsection.
14 (2), (3) Repealed by Session Laws 1981, c. 383, s. 3.
15 (4) All other claims shall be disbursed according to the order set out in
16 G.S. 28A-19-6.
17 Notwithstanding the foregoing provisions of this subsection, the clerk shall pay, out of funds
18 provided the deceased pursuant to G.S. 111-18 and Part 3 of Article 2 of Chapter 108A of the
19 General Statutes of North Carolina, Statutes, any lawful claims for care provided by an adult care
20 home to the deceased, incurred not more than 90 days prior to the deceased's death. After the
21 death of a spouse who died intestate the decedent and after the disbursements have been made in
22 accordance with this subsection, the balance in the clerk's hands belonging to the estate of the
23 decedent shall be paid to the surviving spouse, and if there is no surviving spouse, the clerk shall
24 pay it to the heirs or beneficiaries in proportion to their respective interests.
25 (g) The clerk shall not be required to publish notice to creditors.
26 (h) Whenever an administrator is appointed after a clerk of superior court has received
27 any money pursuant to this section, the clerk shall pay to the administrator all funds which have
28 not been disbursed. The clerk shall receive no commissions for payments made to the
29 administrator, and the administrator shall receive no commissions for receiving such payments."
30 SECTION 4.6. Section 4.5 of this act is effective when it becomes law. The
31 remainder of this Part becomes effective January 1, 2026, and applies to petitions filed on or after
32 that date.
